UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440767890088X
AB  - Multidimensional scaling algorithms seek N points, in M-dimensional space, whose interpoint distances match in some sense the experimental dissimilarities of N variables. The dissimilarity coefficients may be qualitative and of diverse kinds. For M = 2 or 3, complex relationships can be depicted graphically and summarized succinctly. Prevalence of bulky correlation matrices in econometric research suggests multidimensional scaling may prove a helpful tool.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - A new method of estimating Engel elasticities
AU  - Kakwani, Nanak
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 8
IS  - 1
SP  - 103
EP  - 110
PY  - 1978
DA  - 1978/08/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(78)90092-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407678900921
AB  - For the purpose of estimating expenditure (or income) elasticities, one needs to specify the form of the Engel function. This paper considers a new equation of the Engel function which is based on a new coordinate system for the Lorenz curve discussed recently by Kakwani and Podder (Econometrica, 1976). This new equation of the Lorenz curve is fitted to the expenditure data and then the expenditure elasticities are derived in terms of the estimated parameters of the Lorenz curve for total expenditure and expenditure on each commodity. Using Indonesian data, it has been demonstrated that the proposed equation of the Engel function performs better than the other well-known forms of Engel function on the basis of two criteria, viz, goodness of fit and adding-up criterion (emphasised by Nicholson, Journal of the Royal Statistical Society A, 1949).
ER  - 
